  "verdict": "B1 FAILS -- Trilha B STOPS here, per the pre-registered decision rule. Only 6/21 (29%) of the evaluable pilot patients show significant interoceptive-boundary nonlinearity vs IAAFT (3 of 24 downloaded segments were too short to yield >= 200 R-peaks), below the pre-registered 60% bar. On I-CARE ECG the interoceptive boundary does not carry structure beyond a linear-Gaussian null in a majority of patients, so the CBRA boundary residual is not reliably estimable and the dissociation is not executable on this substrate. Three honesty notes: (i) the initial fixed-threshold R-peak detector was inadequate on I-CARE's heterogeneous ECG and was replaced with an adaptive Pan-Tompkins detector BEFORE reading this result -- and the fix made the negative STRONGER (29% vs a spuriously-higher 42% on the broken detector), so it is a defect fix, not outcome tuning; (ii) of the 6 'structured' patients 3 have |T_rev| > 0.5, large enough to reflect ectopic beats/arrhythmia (endemic post-arrest) rather than genuine interoceptive nonlinearity, so even 29% is likely an OVER-count; (iii) post-arrest ECG is heavily confounded by sedation, targeted temperature management, and pressors, any of which flattens interoceptive nonlinearity. This is a pre-registered, publishable negative: combined with Fase 0 (I-CARE is the ONLY public dataset carrying the I+/I- contrast), it means the CBRA dissociation is effectively not executable on available public data -- the boundary residual is not estimable where the contrast exists -- which is an added estimability condition on \u00a714.1, not a contortion. B2 (MR sub-criticality) and B3 (matched dissociation) are NOT run, exactly as the pre-registration requires when B1 fails.",
